ing together the best new work on contemporary media practices, technologies, and policies, the essayists in Global Currents argue that neither of these extreme views accurately represents the role of media technology today. New ways of thinking about film, television, music, and the internet demonstrate that it is not only media technologies that affect the cultures into which they are introduced-it is just as likely that the receiving culture will change the media. Topics covered in the volume include copyright law and surveillance technology, cyber activism in the African Diaspora, transnational monopolies and local television industries, the marketing and consumption of "global music," "click politics" and the war on Afghanistan, the techno-politics of distance education, artificial intelligence and global legal institutions, and traveling and "squatting" in digital space. Balanced between major theoretical positions and original field research, the selections address the political and cultural meanings that surround and configure new technologies.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aCommunication, International. 0aGlobalization. 0aMass media and technology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBourdon, Jerome1 aBraman, Sandra1 aCiecko, Anne1 aEverett, Anna1 aFoner, Lenny1 aJones, Steve1 aLarkin, Brian1 aMiller, Toby1 aOhmer, Susan1 aOren, Tasha G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetro, Patrice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSands, Peter1 aSreberny, Annabelle1 aTaylor, Timothy08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978081354249242